Dear Ian,

Thank you granting access to the TtH and TtM flex source at
http://sourceforge.net/projects/tth. I downloaded tth4_00.tar.gz and
followed your instructions in the file tth/README. It does indeed
compile working tth and ttm executables under Debian. I realize
you have spent thousands of hours writing and revising these
very useful programs.

There are a number of problems with your copyright license in the
file tth/README which would need to fixed before it would fully comply
with the Debian Free Software Guidelines (DFSG). These are:---

1. Conflicting licenses in other files. My list of files with
   copyright license information is:

       tth/README
       tth/manual/ttm_manual.tex
       tth/manual/tth_manual.tex
       tth/manual/split/sec14.html
       tth/manual/split/tth_manual.html
       tth/ttmC/README
       tth/ttmL/README
       tth/TtMdir/readme.ttm
       tth/tthfunc/tars/tthdynamic/tth_manual.tex
       tth/tthfunc/tars/tthdynamic/tth_manual.html
       tth/tthgold/install.bat
       tth/tthgold/license.txt

   Ideally tth should have one license.txt file and wherever
   else you have a copyright claim you add the taglines:

   You may use this software only under the terms and conditions in
   the file license.txt originally included in the source tar file.

   If you have two licenses use different filenames and
   clearly identify which license applies to each file. Ideally
   one would have two separate tar if this were the case.

2. The copyright license should be titled "Copyright License"
   unless in a file on its own.

3. tth/README does not make it clear that the license applies
   to all software in the tth4_00.tar.gz file. What about ttm?

4. The word "freely" has many meanings. It is not clear which
   of these meanings applies.

5. The disclaimer in the second paragraph should be more general in
   who it covers and specific in what it covers against.

6. It has not been found compatible with the GPL which
   is a DFSG requirement.

7. Debian prefers the GPL version 3 as it extends free software and
   protects against software patent abuse but accepts many other
   boilerplate licenses as satisfying the DFSG. It has been tested in
   law courts of the USA and other countries and found to mean what is
   claimed.

Boilerplate like the Expat license takes the work out of drafting
a license which satisfies the DFSG.

